metadata.name: Reconnaissance #273
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they‚Äôre recon from another planet‚Äôs civilization ‚Äî one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium ‚ÄúThis is Mars,‚Äù Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands ‚Äî and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what‚Äôs next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.
Created with p5.js

TENDER x Nat Sarkissian
May 2022

metadata.name: Garden, Monoliths #190
metadata.description:
"Garden, Monoliths" is the result of an algorithm that started in April 2021. It was called "Grass.js".
Spring was blooming all around the house, taking over the stones and remnants of ancient battles that stood here. Inspiration was everywhere.
The initial goal was to use mathematical formulas for creating patterns inspired by the density of nature, that could be used by a pen plotter, so it kept focusing on outputting vector lines. This history and practice produced a graphical style based on line strokes, plus occasionally some transparent, filled shapes.
Each artwork will be either "Garden" or "Monolith", for they are variations of two existing designs from the workshop.

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #12
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: stigmergy #173
metadata.description:
Stigmergy is a method of decentralized organization in which agents communicate by leaving traces in a shared environment. This piece simulates a kind of stigmergy among a large population of particles. Each particle leaves a trail behind it as it moves, and determines its direction of motion based on the trails around it. The rules for how a particle should move based on its surroundings were created with a user-guided evolutionary process.

Press "c" to capture a 2048x2048 image of the simulation. You can also press the spacebar to pause/unpause the simulation, and press "n" while paused to move the simulation forward a single step.
